'''''Tatooine Ghost''''' is a [[Star Wars Legends|''Star Wars'' Legends]] novel written by [[Troy Denning]]. It was first published in hardcover by [[Del Rey]] on [[March 4]], [[2003]]. A paperback edition was published on [[December 30]], 2003, and it includes Denning's short story "[[Corphelion Interlude]]" and novella ''[[A Forest Apart]]''.

Set in [[8 ABY/Legends|8 ABY]], ''Tatooine Ghost'' follows [[Leia Organa Solo/Legends|Leia Organa]] to [[Tatooine/Legends|Tatooine]], where she discovers the history of her [[Parent/Legends|father]] [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker]], connecting the [[Original trilogy|original]] and [[prequel trilogy]] characters.

An [[Tatooine Ghost (abridged audiobook)|abridged audiobook]] of the novel is available.

==Publisher's summary==
''Han Solo and Leia Organa take center stage, and stunning revelations from the past play a critical role in shaping the future, as the ''New York Times'' bestselling author of ''Star Wars'': The New Jedi Order: ''Star by Star'' now turns to a crucial chapter in the classic ''Star Wars'' saga.''

''The deaths of Darth Vader and Emperor Palpatine and victory at the Battle of Endor by no means spelled the end of the Empire. In the aftermath, the New Republic has faced a constant struggle to survive and grow. And now a new threat looms: a masterpiece of Alderaanian art, lost in transit after the planet's destruction, has resurfaced on the black market. Offered at auction, it will command a handsome price, but its greatest value lies in the vital secret it conceals the key to a code used to communicate with New Republic agents deep undercover within the Empire. Discovery of the key by Imperial forces would spell certain disaster. The only option is recovery, and Han, Leia, Chewbacca, and C-3PO have been dispatched to Tatooine to infiltrate the auction.''

''But trouble is waiting when they arrive: an Imperial Star Destroyer is orbiting Tatooine on the lookout for Rebels; a mysterious stranger at the auction seems to recognize Leia; and an Imperial officer's aggressive bidding for the Alderaanian painting could foil the Solos' mission. When a dispute erupts into violence, and the painting vanishes in the chaos, Han and Leia are thrust into a desperate race to reclaim it before Imperial troops or a band of unsavory treasure-peddlers get there first.''

''Dangerous as the chase is, for Leia it leads into especially dark territory. Already haunted by the specter of her infamous father, and fearful that his evil may infect future generations, she has suffered a disturbing Force-vision of Luke turning to the dark side. As she battles beside Han against marauding TIE fighters, encroaching stormtroopers, and Tatooine's savage Tusken Raiders, Leia's struggle with the warring emotions inside her culminates in the discovery of an extraordinary link to the past. And as long-buried secrets and truths at last emerge, she faces a moment of reckoning that will forever alter her destiny and that of the New Republic.''

==Plot summary==
[[Leia Skywalker Organa Solo]], her [[Marriage/Legends|husband]] [[Han Solo/Legends|Han]], his [[Wookiee/Legends|Wookiee]] companion, [[Chewbacca/Legends|Chewbacca]], and their [[Protocol droid/Legends|protocol droid]], [[C-3PO/Legends|C-3PO]], travel to the [[Desert/Legends|desert]] [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Tatooine/Legends|Tatooine]]. Their mission is to recover an [[Alderaanian/Legends|Alderaanian]] work of art, titled the ''[[Killik Twilight]]'', because within ''Killik Twilight'' lies a communications device that acts as a link between the [[New Republic/Legends|New Republic]] and their [[Spy/Legends|spies]] acting as undercover agents all around the dying [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]]. The [[Millennium Falcon/Legends|''Millennium Falcon'']] gets into a dogfight with Imperial forces, led by [[Grand Admiral/Legends|Grand Admiral]] [[Mitth'raw'nuruodo/Legends|Thrawn]], but manages to arrive on the surface of Tatooine and dock under cover from the enemy forces. 

Then, under disguises at a local [[Cantina/Legends|cantina]], the [[Solo family/Legends|Solos]] attend an auction there in order to retrieve the ''Killik Twilight.'' One of the items on sale is [[Holocube/Legends|holocube]] that shows a [[Hologram/Legends|holographic]] image of the late [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker]] back in [[32 BBY/Legends|32 BBY]] just after he won the [[Boonta Eve Classic/Legends|Boonta Eve Podrace]]. Leia is distraught at the image of who had once been her [[Parent/Legends|father]], whom she has only known as the evil Darth Vader in the [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebel Alliance's]] [[Galactic Civil War/Legends|war]] with the Empire. The image is sold, nevertheless, to another auctioneer, and the disturbance of the image wrought upon by Leia leads into a conversation between her and Han, discussing the prospects about having [[Youngling/Legends|children]]. Leia is reluctant to do so, because of her [[Skywalker family/Legends|biological family's]] line in [[The Force/Legends|the Force]] and of her father's legacy as Vader. She fears that it may be too possible for whatever children she and Han tend to bear one day will fall to the [[Dark side of the Force/Legends|dark side]].

By the time the ''Killik Twilight'' is up for grabs, violence breaks out from the Imperial forces attending the auction who intend to retrieve the art piece. During the fight, the ''Killik Twilight'' is lost. And so Han and Leia embark on a journey through Tatooine in order to retrieve the art piece, battling the Imperial forces and [[Tusken Raider/Legends|Tusken Raiders]] with the help of [[Jawa/Legends|Jawas]] and a [[Squib/Legends|Squib]] trio, [[Emala]], [[Sligh]], and [[Grees]]. During their voyage, Leia finds out more about her late father's past, and runs into Anakin's old friend, [[Kitster Chanchani Banai]], who reveals to her what her father was like before he left Tatooine under the guidance of the late [[Qui-Gon Jinn/Legends|Qui-Gon Jinn]]. Leia also retrieves a [[Holojournal/Legends|holojournal]] recorded by [[Shmi Skywalker Lars/Legends|Shmi]], revealing details of her life in between Anakin's departure from Tatooine to his return to his home planet.

Eventually, Leia finally comes to terms with her father's legacy and no longer fears that her children will fall to the dark side, after she learns that her father was once a young, innocent [[Gender/Legends|boy]], and a fairly decent individual prior to his fall as Vader. She and Han then retrieve the communications device from the ''Killik Twilight'' while the art piece itself is taken by Grand Admiral Thrawn's forces. The Solos, Chewbacca and C-3PO leave Tatooine, and Leia is at peace with her lineage.

==Continuity==
[[Del Rey]] books published ''Tatooine Ghost'' in the midst of producing the [[Star Wars: The New Jedi Order|''New Jedi Order'']] series. It was a step back in the timeline, being set during the time frame dominated by the [[Bantam Spectra]] novels of the [[Wikipedia: 1990s|1990's]]. Coming as it did after [[Star Wars: Episode I The Phantom Menace|Episodes I]] and [[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones|II]], ''Tatooine Ghost'' was able to reference the prequels as the Bantam books never could and extrapolated that [[Leia Organa Solo/Legends|Leia]] was able to overcome her resistance to having [[Youngling/Legends|children]] by learning more of [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker's]] past. Playing a role in the book is [[Grand Admiral/Legends|Grand Admiral]] [[Mitth'raw'nuruodo/Legends|Thrawn]], who goes unnamed since the main [[New Republic/Legends|New Republic]] heroes do not know of his existence until after the events of the [[Star Wars: The Thrawn Trilogy|''Thrawn Trilogy'']].<ref name="ERC" />

The [[2012]] reference book ''[[The Essential Reader's Companion]]'' dates the events of ''Tatooine Ghost'' to [[8 ABY/Legends|8 ABY]], following the events of the novel ''[[The Courtship of Princess Leia]]'' ([[1994]]), short story "[[Corphelion Interlude]]" ([[2003]]), and novella ''[[A Forest Apart]]'' (2003), and preceding the novel ''[[Heir to the Empire]]'' ([[1991]]).<ref name="ERC" />

